{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"page_content": "The null hypothesis, H0, is that the profit that summer ads yield is less than or equal to the profits that winter ads yield.\n\nThe alternative hypothesis, H1, is that the profit that summer ads yield is greater than the profits that winter ads yield.\n\nmean_summer <- mean(summer$profit) mean_winter <- mean(winter$profit)\n\nn_summer <- nrow(summer) n_winter <- nrow(winter)\n\nt <- (mean_summer - mean_winter)/sqrt(variance_summer/n_summer +\n\nvariance_winter/n_winter)\n\nv_numerator <- ((variance_summer/n_summer) + (variance_winter/n_winter))\u02c62 v_denominator <- ((variance_summer/n_summer)\u02c62/(n_summer - 1)) +\n\n((variance_winter/n_winter)\u02c62/(n_winter - 1))\n\nv <- v_numerator/v_denominator\n\np <- 1 - pt(t, v) p\n\n## [1] 0.7550194\n\nThus, with a p-value of 0.7550194, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, and conclude that the profit that summer ads yield is greater than the profits that winter ads yield.\n\n11\n\nPart 2C: What if you wanted to compare all seasons at once at the \u03b1 = 0.05 significance level with a familywise error of \u03b1F W E = 0.05? Run an appropriate test (or series of tests) and comment on your results.\n\nThe null hypothesis, H0, is that there is no difference between the average profit for each season. The alternative hypothesis, H1, is that at least one season has a different average profit than the other seasons.\n\nWe can compare all seasons at once using a Bonferroni multiple comparison procedure.\n\nput ANOVA first\n\npairwise.t.test(ads$profit, ads$season, p.adj = \"bonferroni\")\n\n## ## Pairwise comparisons using t tests with pooled SD ## ## data: ads$profit and ads$season ## ## ## spring 1 ## summer 1 ## winter 1 ## ## P value adjustment method: bonferroni\n\nfall spring summer\n\n1 1\n\n- 1\n\nNo tests were found to be significant.\n\nThe adjusted p-value for the mean difference in profit between any two seasons is so large that the null hypothesis can not be rejected, and we must conclude that there is no difference between the mean profit for each season.", "metadata": {"source": "./documents/University of Rochester/computational intro to stats final project report.pdf"}, "type": "Document"}}